          "title": "The chapter's canonical resonance: land, lot, and ultimate inheritance",
          "body": "Numbers 34 belongs to a canonical thread that runs from Genesis 15 (the covenant boundary promise to Abraham) through Joshua 14-21 (the partial fulfillment under Joshua) through Ezekiel 47-48 (the eschatological reallotment) to the New Testament's expansion of the promise. Paul declares in Romans 4:13 that Abraham's inheritance is not merely Canaan but 'the world' — the particular land promise becomes the template for the cosmic inheritance of the redeemed (cf. Matthew 5:5, 'the meek shall inherit the earth'). The lot (goral, v. 13) that distributes Canaan among the tribes reappears in Psalm 16:5-6 as the language of personal covenant portion with God ('Thou art the portion of mine inheritance and of my cup... the lines are fallen unto me in pleasant places'). What Israel experienced as surveyed real estate, the psalmist internalized as personal covenant intimacy. Canaan is not merely geography; it is the shape of every covenant promise that God makes specific enough to trace on a map."
